No doubt, Kenyans are better off today than they were on December 12, 1964 when the country became a republic.
Fifty-six years later, there have been triumphs, failures and missed chances.
Jubilee came to power  on a promise of a resurgent economy but the country is facing a recession, partly blamed on the Covid-19 pandemic.
Runaway national debt, a weakening shilling, public health crisis, rising levels of poverty, obsession with political machinations and uncertainty in education show a party and individuals that were not prepared to govern the country.





The shilling is trading against the dollar at Sh111 to Sh118.
The weakening of the currency means importers now pay more for goods.
Debt level
Debt stood at Sh1.8 trillion.
The debt accumulated by the country in less than eight years has surpassed what Kenya borrowed from 1963 to 2012.
When Mr Kenyatta became President, the country’s debt stood at Sh1.8 trillion. By June this year, it was Sh6.7 trillion.
The shilling has weakened by more than 7.4 per cent against the dollar, having opened 2020 at 101.34 and is now at 108.83.
It means the interest on the country’s loans is also going up.
The country’s health sector is in a crisis, with workers on strike as hospitals continue receiving Covid-19 patients amid rising infections and deaths.



