Nurses and clinical officers at public hospitals boycotted duty early this week to press for higher pay and better working conditions.
The President has kept his political boat going as the country gears up for elections in 2022.
But his juggling skills will be tested to the limits as he drums up support for the Building Bridges Initiative (BBI), a process meant to change parts of the country’s Constitution.
The BBI has faced opposition from many quarters. The President is expected to implore Kenyans to pass it at the referendum slated for next year.
Many challenges
Senate Majority Whip Irungu Kang’ata, an ally of the President in the ruling Jubilee party, admits that have been many challenges.
“Jubilee has delivered on many of its promises. The economy has grown at an average of six per cent and the middle class has expanded,” the Murang’a senator told the Saturday Nation.
“Expectant women are delivering free of charge at government hospitals, and the National Health Insurance Fund (NHIF) cover has been expanded. Transition rate has increased in education due to free day schooling.”
Mr Kang’ata added that cyclical ethnic conflicts during presidential elections have affected the country’s growth trajectory.



