Elgeyo Marakwet Senator Kipchumba Murkomen says Jubilee’s first term will be remembered for public service but the second term has been characterised by infighting.
“Jubilee did a lot in education and health from 2013 to 2017. At the beginning of its second term, the government came up with the Big Four Agenda, which was going to be a culmination of its strategy after 10 years,” Mr Murkomen told the Saturday Nation. 
Infrastructure
“Unfortunately, the ruling party has wasted the second term on wrangles and infighting. It is s a paradox because the fights are around a project disguised as building Bridges. In the end, the quest for unity has become the greatest cause of wrangles in the government and Jubilee thus undermining public service.”
Prof Macharia Munene of the United States International University-Africa says it is still early to judge President Kenyatta and his administration.
“They have one and half years to go. They have done well in some areas like infrastructure and done poorly in others like health, though they may blame the Covid-19 pandemic. Passing a judgement is premature,” he said.
Meanwhile, technology giant Google will mark today’s Jamhuri Day with a doodle appearing on its search service homepage.



